column214: This is an interesting experiement. My strategy was to devide slightly more on A and relatively less on B. However the computer generated rate was very random and it was hard to keep the earning high. But generally I tend to set more A after seeing several A multipliers under 1  and set more B or half and half after seeing several large A multipliers.
I lost some opportunities to get a larger amount  which I can guess right. sometimes I am a little too conservative.

A large part of the experiment was based on luck. I feel like this is relevant to real-life investing because there is always risk and luck involved. I later started keeping a minimum e.g. 1 dollar that I am sure that I will get in asset B and using the excess money to invest in asset A.

As the periods went on  I slowly decreased the percentage that I invested in asset A. Sometimes when I saw A's multiplier continually be over 1  I would increase the amount I invested in A.  | Everything in this experiment was clear.

I decided that taking the risk with asset A generally gave me greater rewards than being safe with asset B. The proportions I determined between the two assets was generally determined by my guesses on what ratio asset A would be next. I found that asset C was unsuccessful.
It was very interesting experience. Thanks.
I liked how one of the assets was random..so I cannot expect the future data. | How about I sensed that there was some pattern..(somehow)..but still it was random. | The experiment was clear.
